    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "it seems like nitrogen is a big one. is that why the bottom leaves go first? kind of feels like something is just eating all the good stuff before it can get to the top part of the plant. how do i know if it's actually nitrogen or if something else is stealing it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, you've hit on a key point; nitrogen is a mobile nutrient, meaning the plant moves it from older, lower leaves to support new, growing foliage at the top. It's like the plant is prioritizing its future, sacrificing the older leaves to keep the top strong. If the lower leaves are yellowing while the new growth is fine, nitrogen deficiency is a very strong suspect, though it could also be potassium or magnesium showing similar symptoms.\n\nTo tell for sure, you could perform a simple soil test, which is the most definitive way to know what your soil is lacking. Alternatively, you can look for other signs: if the yellowing is accompanied by stunted growth or pale, weak stems, it leans heavily toward nitrogen. If the yellowing is more mottled or has dark spots, you might be dealing with a fungal issue or a different mineral imbalance.\n\nIt's a bit like a scavenger hunt, and the soil test is the map! If you can't test it, a quick application of a nitrogen-rich fertilizer (like one with a higher first number, N-P-K) should give you a quick visual answer. Just be careful not to overdo it, or you risk burning the roots",
      "source": "target",
