    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if it is nitrogen that is being drained from the bottom, how do i actually get the pH level right so the plant can actually absorb it? i dont want the nutrients to just sit there if the soil is too acidic or something.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A proper pH level is absolutely critical, because if the soil is too acidic or too alkaline, the plant can't unlock those nutrients, even if they are physically present in the soil. For most tomatoes, you want a slightly acidic to neutral pH, ideally between 6.0 and 6.8. If your soil is too acidic, you might need to add agricultural lime to raise the pH, and if it's too alkaline, elemental sulfur can help bring it down.\n\nIt's a delicate balance, and getting it right is like teaching a picky eater to accept a new flavor! You don't want to shock the system, so start small with your amendments.\n\nI always recommend getting a soil test first, because trying to guess the pH adjustments is like trying to navigate a minefield blindfolded—you might end up making the problem worse! A soil test will tell you exactly how far off you are from the sweet spot.",
